{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346954/1937092701/0430.xml":{"full_text":"HUGEST CANAL FOR IRRIGATION\nNEARLY READY-'MELONBASKET\nIS IN HAST MAN-MADE CARDEN\n.Expected To Be Completed Nov. 1\nFicod Control Feature Will Work In\nConjunction With Boulder Dam\nBT ARTHUR N. SUVERKRUP\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nCalexico, Cal., September 27.\nThe world\u2019s largest Irrigation canal\nwill be completed within the next\ntwo months, at least by November\n1.\nEngineers In charge of the exca\nvation of the 130,000,000 project said\ntheir work now Is In Its final stages.\nWhen completed, and water is\nturned Into the big ditch, the\ntherat of disastrous summer\ndrouth, and equally disastrous\nColorado River floods forever will\nbe eliminated from the Imperial\nValley melon basket of the United\nStates.\nThe flood control feature of the\ncanal will operate In connection\nwith that other gigantic project of\nthe Southwest\u2014the Boulder Dam.\nCHAIRMAN\nDANIEL MORELLI\nThe Duce Society celebrated the\nfifth anniversary of Its existence\nyesterday afternoon and evening\nwith a reception for its members\nand friends in Turners\u2019 hall.' Over\n6(11 visited the scene during the\ncourse of the afternoon and eve\nning. Umberto Santopletro was\nmuster of ceremonies. A splendid\nprogram of entertainment was\npresented. Daniel Mroelli was\nchairman of the committee of ar\nrungements.\nThe guests included Thomas P.\nKelly, executive secretary to Mayor\nFrank Hayes; Judge Edward A.\nMascolo. Alderman Charles P. Sci\nuloo, Carmine G. Ciprlano, Ralph\nCoppeto, Frederick W. Palomba,\nMiss Doris Jacaruso, Dr. Rudolph\nA. Damlanl. Nicholas Zappone,\nJohn DePastfno, Joseph Clcchiello,\nPhilip Coppeto, Louis Brla, Gen\neroso Ruggiero, and James Aldori\nsio.\nThe committee Included Daniel\nMorelli, chairman; Antonio Di\nGennaro, Nicola Guliottl, Rolando\nV. Sica, Lorento Fusco, oDmenico\nDerasino. Nicola Mangino, Rocco\nDevlno.'Pasquale an dJohn Dom\ninzo, Celestino Calabrese and A.\nClariello.\nEASTERN STAR HAS\nFASHION SHOW\nWalter Trimble Directs;\nLocal Women Act as\nModels\nCHESHIRE NEWS\nCheshire, Sept. 27\u2014Friday eve\nning a successful fashion show was\nconducted in the town hall by Cres\ncent chapter, Order of Eastern Star,\nunder the direction of Walter Trim\nble.\nProper and Improper methods in\ndress in regard to style color and\nmaterial were shown with Mrs.\nLuke H. Stapleton, Mrs. Wilbur J.\nMoore. Mrs. Raymond E. Warner,\nMrs. Eugeno Lawrence, Miss Blenda\nGoddard as models. Entertainment\nwas given by Mrs. Joseph H. Dou\ncette. Betty Durand, Eleanor Luke,\nMerrill Doucette, Evelyn Behrmann\nand Norman Van Burcn.\nMr. and Mrs. James H. Darcey of\nPaul Ney road are the guests in\nNew York city of Capt. W. Neville\nPrengel, who was a visitor here re\ncently.\nMrs. Russell B. Nichols has re\nturned to her home on Horton\navenue from Richmond, L. I., where\nshe was the guest of her sister, Mrs.\nM. 8. Rahner.\nMr. and Mrs. Hiram Andrews and\nMr. and Mrs. Earl Minor of Mill\ndale road were at the fair in Spring\nfield on Friday.\nCorporal Leroy Harper and Lieut.\nHubert M. Rlgney were on duty\nwith Co. E 102 Inf. (The Ohatfield\nGuard) at the Greystone Rifle\nRange Sunday, where the company\nwas engaged in record firing.\nArthur De Vylder, of Willow street\nhas bought the farm of John Glass\nnap of Mllldale road.\nBobby Nichols played with the\nHillhouse high school football team\nin Derby on Saturday and his play\nreceived much praise. He is a stu\ndent at Hillhouse.\nHANDCUFFED MAN CAUGHT\nWllllmantlc. Conn., Sept. 27\u2014\n(UP)\u2014New York police notified lo\ncal authorities today that Harry\nEreshena, 20, Mansfield, who es\ncaped here last week wearing hand\ncuffs and minus a shoe, had been\ncaptured in that citly while riding\nwith a truckload of chickens.\nEreshena, paroled from Cheshire\nreformatory, was arrested Tuesday\nwhile allegedly. attempting, to bur\nglarize a department store.\nMore than one-third of Italy's\nalcohol is now obtained from sugar\nl\nWith excavation complete,\nJerome H. Fertlg, engineer In\ncharge of. the work here for the\nU. S. Reclamation Service, said\nwater will be flowing In the ditch\nby the spring of 1639 making\navailable for cultivation 500,000\nacres of land, the largest Irriga\ntion district In North America, if\nnot in the world.\nEngineering Problems Difficult\nIn the construction of the canal,\ntremendous engineering problems\nwere overcome before the opera\ntion of the big ditch could be as\nsured of success.\nUndesirable silt deposits, which\nhave been a problem to Imperial\nValley farmers since Colorado\nRiver water first was diverted for\nIrrigation, will be eliminated by a\ndesiltlng plant which will sluice\nheavier silt back Into the river be\nlow Imperial Dam.\nColorado River water will enter\nthe canal from Imperial Dam, 20\nmiles above Yuma, Ariz.\nBelow Yuma the canal will\nparallel the Mexican border for a\nshort distance then circle north\nward soon to veer back toward the\nborder near Calexico. The ser\npentine 80-mlle course of the canal\nends in the Westside Main Canal\nat the western limit of Imperial\nValley\u2019s cultivated area.\nWhen the canal begins to serve\nvalley farms ranchers no more will\nworry about how much water is\nbeing taken below the border.\nPresent Flow Restricted\nThe present canal flows for miles\nthrough lower California and the\nrich agricultural area there has\nfirst claim on the water.\nImperial Valley\u2019s early settlers\nproposed the idea 20 years ago,\nand In the long fight to obtain\nlegislatidn and funds from the\nFederal government, had to sell\nthe nation on feasibility of the\nproject as a national asset.\nFour pbwer drops will be con\nstructed on the canal for the Im\nperial Irrigation District under the\ncontract with the Reclamation Bu\nreau, and revenue derived from the\nsale of electric power generated by\ncanal waters Is expected to repay\nthe entire cost of construction in\n40 years.\nFunds for building the first\npower plant were made available\nin August when a temporary court\norder was signed In Washington,\nreleasing PWA money for this\npurpose.\nCanal Crosses River\nAdditional structures along the\nlength of the canal will Include,\nbesides the four power drops, three\ndrops to take care of natural fall:\nhighway bridges where the canal\ngoes under roadways; flood over\nchutes In the desert to protect\nbanks of the canal In heavy rain\nstorms; a series of turnouts to\nfurnish water to farm lands served\nby present laterals; and siphons,\nIncluding the New River siphon, n\n$300,000 unit will carry the all\nAmerican canal across New River in\ntwo steel pipes, IS feet in diameter,\nsupported on concrete pilings 12 feet\nabove the water level, for a dis\ntance of 374 feet.\nUninterrupted continuation of\nthe canal project was assured\nearlier this year by inclusion ot\n$1,600,000 ih the Department of\ninterior appropriation bill.\nAuthorized together with Boulder\nDam b yact of Congress in Decem\nber, 1928, construction of the canal\nwas approved by PWA in October,\n1933, and $6,000,000 made available\nto start work.\nExcavation was begun early In\n1934. Work at Imperial Dam, where\nthe water will enter the canal,\nshould be completed next spring.\nKidnaped Chicagoan And His Wife\n\u2014Acme Telephoto\n\u2014Acme Telephoto\nCharles R. Ross, 72, wealthy re\ntired Chicago manufacturer, who\nwas kidnaped by three armed\nmen while riding In a suburb of\nthe city with his secretary, Flor\nence Frelhage, 40, who was forced\nfrom the car and told that It was\na kidnaping.\nMr*. Charles S. Ross, wife of\nthe kidnaped Chicagoan, who was\novercome by the reported kidnap\ning of her husband by three arm\ned men as he was riding with his\nsecretary in a suburb of the city.\nARIZONA ARCHEOLOGISTS UNCOVER\n700-YEAR-OLD SUN WORSHIP CENTER\nOF THE PUEBLO INDIAN CULTURE\nBY CARL MeCLUNG\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nKinishba, Fort Apache, Ariz. ,Sept. 27\u2014(UP)\u2014Linking\nthe prehistoric dwellers in this ancient pueblo with highly\ncultured civilizations of the Salt River and the Little Colora\ndo, finds of a summer expedition are being shipped from the\nruin to the state museum at the University of Arizona.\nDefinite proof sun worshipers\nlived In the pueblo some 700 years\nago was unearthed when a thin\nslate, still vividly painted despite\nlong burial, was found depicting the\nsun symbol familiar to all south\nwesterners.\nThe pear-shaped object, about 15\nInches long, was described as the\nprincipal discovery of the summer\u2019s\nexcavation work conducted by Uni\nversity of Arizona field course stu\ndents, under Dr. Byron Cummings\nhead of the archeology department.\nIt was painted In red, yellow, white\nand black, colors believed to have\nbeen used by the Indians to repre\nsent the cardinal directions.\nCom Pictured\nThe plaque was the secnd found\nIn the pueblo, although it repre\nsented first direct evidence of un\nworshlp. Last season, a slate was\nunearthed bearing representation of\na stalk of corn.\nSimilar tablets have. been found\nIn both the Little Colorado district,\nto the north, and the Salt River\ndrainage area, to the south, Dr.\nCummings said. Finding of the\nplaques at Kinishba Is proof the\npueblo In Its heyday was a con\nnecting link for the two cultured\ncivilizations, he held.\nDuring ten broiling summer\nmonths, the group completely ex\ncavated 12 rooms which were un\ndisturbed for seven centuries, after\nabandonment by their Indian own\ners. Several chambers were en\ntered. Another expedition may be\nmade next summer.\nRestore 10 Rooms\nTen rooms were reconstructed In\ntheir original form. Sixteen stu\ndents, with 24 Apache Indians as\nhelpers, aided In the work.\nThe two main groups of ruins,\nbelieved to contain some 700 roms.\nwere fenced this summer as first\nstep toward the university\u2019s goal of\nconverting the pueblo Into a nation\nal monument. Four other, smaller\nmounds He within the fenced area.\nA series of other articles which\nforge links In the chain of evidence\nproving Kinishba a meeting place\nof cultures, were brought to light as\nthe explorers searched the habita\ntions. Small but easily Identifiable\nfragments of coton cloth, which had\nbeen wrapped around a child dur\ning a burial ceremony, were found\nIn the grave.\nBasket Impressions\nIn an adjoining room, Impressions\nof a large grass storage basket, elm\nOarr Brothers freed On Bond\n\u2014nwiic jciepnoiu;\nPhotographed during recess of their examining trail, Jack, Roy and\nDr. E. 8. Oarr, bottom to top, above, are pictured above outside the\nShelbyville, Ky\u201e courtroom, shortly before being set free on bond to\nawait grand Jury action in the shooting of Brig. Gen. Henry H. Den\nhardt, accused slayer of their sister, Mrs. Verna Garr Taylor. Pictured\nbelow at the trial are Mrs. Taylor\u2019s daughters, Mrs. Mary Pryor Brown,\nleft, and Mias Fraacee Taylor, i\nliar to some made today by Papago\nand Pima Indians, were found. This\ntype of basket also Is found in the\nGlia Mountains.\nA storage room for some prehis\ntoric \u201cmedicine man\" yielded meteo\nric Iron balls several Inches In dia\nmeter which had been worn as fe\ntishes. Pieces of quartz, crystal, ob\nsidian and bits of human hair were\ndiscovered in his belongings.\nThe superb skill of the potters of\nKlnlshba was evidenced by a large\nblack and white olla, or storage jar,\ndiscovered In one of the better pre\nserved sections. The design was\nnegative, black having been added\nso that yrhlte showing through car\nried the design\u2014and bore triangles\nand large circles. Dr. Cummings\ntheorized the latter might be consid\nered sun symbols. The Jar was 15\nInches high, 19 inches In dlametei\nand almost spherical In shape.\nPRETTYWEDDING\nIS HELD TODAY\nFellowship Night to Be\nObserved Assembly\nHeld at South School\nOAKVILLE\nOakville, Sept. 27 An attrac\ntive wedding took place this morn\ning at 9:00 o'clock at St. Mary\nMagdalen's church, when Miss\nMadeline Ursal Vaicekauskas,\ndaughter of Ll:\\ and rMs. Joseph\nVaicekauskas, of French street, be\ncame the bride of Joseph Donald\nMasl, son of Mr. and Mrs. Donald\nMasl of French street.\nThe church was prettily decorated\nwith palms, ferns and cut flowers.\nThe organist, Mrs. Maud Donahue,\narranged a special program of wed\nding music.\ne\u2019sB Rev. Thomas McGarry, pastor\nperformed the ceremony and nup\ntial mass which followed In the pros\nence of a large gathering of rela\ntives and friends.\nThe maid of honor was Miss Dora\nFUlpone, and the best man, Alfred\nRinaldi.\nThe bride wore a gown of white\nsatin, princess style, with train,\nhigh neckline, long sleeves, puffed\nat the shoulder and tight fitting to\nthe Anger tip. She wore a long veil\nof tulle, caught In cap shape with a\ncrown of orange blossoms, and car\nried a shower bouquet of white\nroses, lilies of the valley and swan\nsonla.\nThe maid ol' honor, Miss Fillpone\nwore a gown of changeable moire,\nprincess style, puff sleeves. She wore\na silver colored hat, and silver\nshoes. She carried a bouquet of\ndeep pink roses and delphinium.\nThe bride's mother wore a black\nsilk dress with a corsage of garden\nias.\nThe groom\u2019s mother wore i green\nsilk dress with corsage of gardenias.\nA reception was held at Quakers\nInn, Watertown avenue, after the\nceremony. About three hundred\nguests attending.\nThe bride\u2019s gift to her attendant\nwas a bracelet with blue saphlres.\nThe bridegroom\u2019s gift to the best\nman was a birthstone ring.\nMr. and Mrs. Masl left later In\nthe day by motor on a wedding trip\nto Canada. The bride wearing a\nmoroon tweed suit with accessories\nto match. Upon their return they\nwill reside on French street/\nFellowship Night\nFellowship night Is to be observed\nat the Union Congregational church\nThursday evening, October 7 th,\nsponsored by the members of the\nFellowship committee. The elected\ncommittee are: John McLean, chair\nman, Mrs. John McLean, Mr. and\nMrs. David Roger, Mr. and Mrs.\nRobert Whiteside, James Florlan,\nMiss Ruth Clinton, and Miss Esther\nEricson. Stunts and games and a\ngeneral good time is being arranged.\nThis has been a time of good fel\nlowship each year. A special Invita\ntion Is extended to all those who\nhave Joined the church during the\npast year.\nBriefs\nMinstrel rehearsal at the Union\nCongregational church hall Mon\nfay evening at 7:30 o\u2019clock under\nthe direction of Grover Baldwin\nind Sumner A. Libbey. The young\npeople of the parish who are intcr\nssted should report at that time.\nOakville Congregational church is\n\u2022csponsible fbr the devotional per\nod over WATR Monday, Tuesday\nind Wednesday morning at 9:00 a.\nm m i. i i i b. I .jfc F.\nNINE HIGHWAY\nJOBS PLANNED\nCommissioner Macdonald\nCalls for Bids on Pro\ngram of Work\nHighway Commissioner John A\nMacdonald has called for contrac\ntors\u2019 bids on nine town aid road\nprojects, Involving nearly 8 1-1\nmiles of surface improvement ant\nthe construction of two bridges. The\nwork will be done In the towns ol\nGlastonbury, Lyme, Prospect, Shel\nton, Sprague, Trumbull, Voluntown,\nWindsor oLcks and Woodstock.\nLargest of the new Jobs will be\nthat In Glastonbury where 2,800\nfeet of Chestnut Hill road will be\npaved with waterbound macadam,\nOrchard Lane road will be treated\nwith 1,118 feet of rolled gravel, and\na 20-foot reinforced concrete bridge\nand approaches will be built on Was\nsuck road. The Prospect project\nalso calls for waterbound macadam\npavement, measuring 3,812 feet, on\nthe back Waterbury road and the\nStraitsvllle road. Alternate bids on\n2,042 feet of bituminous macadam\nor asphaltic concrete on Bridge\nstreet and Coram avenue in Shel\nton; and 1,828 feet of bituminous\nmacadam, measuring 1,828 feet, and\n2,317 feet of bituminous macadam\ngutters will be built on five sections\nof road In Windsor Locks.\nThe second bridge will be a cor\nrugated, metal arch span over\nGravellly brook In Woodstock. The\nWoodstock project also Includes re\npairs to Spaulding bridge and Wil\ncox bridge. The other projects en\ntail gravel surfacing on varying\nlengths of road.\nSealed bids will be received from\ncontractors at the headquarters of\nthe state highway department in the\nstate office building Hartford, un\ntil 2 p. m\u201e Monday, October 11.\nThe work announced by Commis\nsioner Macdonald is briefly described\nas follows:\nTown Aid Projects\nGlastonbury\u2014About 2,800 feet of\nwaterbound macadam on Chestnut\nHill road, 1,118 feet of rolled bank\nrun gravel on Orchard Lane road,\nand a 20-foot reinforced concrete\nbridge and approaches on Wassuck\nroad.\nLyme\u2014About 7,050 feet of rolled\nbank run gravel on the Grassy Hill\nroad.\nProspect\u2014About 3,812 feet of wa\nterbound macadam on the Back\nWaterbury road and the Straitsvllle\nroad.\nShelton\u2014Alternate bids for about\n2,042 feet of bituminous macadam\nor Colprovla process asphaltic con\ncrete on Bridge street and Coram\navenue.\nSprague About 6,101 feet of\nrolled bank gravel on Franklin\nroad, Pautlpaug Hill road and La\nCroix road.\nTrumbull\u2014About 4,509 feet of\nrolled bank run gravel on Porter\nHill road and Broadway.\nVoluntown\u2014About 12,871 feet of\nrolled bank run gravel on Wylie\nSchool road.\nWindsor Locks\u2014About 1,826 feet\nof bituminous macadam and about\n2,317 feet of bituminous macadam\ngutters on five sections of road.\nWoodstock\u2014A corrugated metal\narch bridge at Gravelly Brook and\nrepairs to Spaulding bridge and\nWilcox bridge.\nKILLED NEAR CHURCH\nLaocnia. N. H., Sept. 26\u2014(UP)\u2014\nMrs. Estelle Gray, 74. was killed by\nrn automobile last night as she\nstepped from South Baptist church\ninto the street.\nMORE ABOUT TAXES By John T. Flynn\nSpectre Of Taxes To Finance\nUnavoidable Spending Puts\nBrake On Business Boom\nBY JOHN X. Flynn\n((Copyright 1937, NEA Service)\nNew York, Sept. 27 We have\nnow seen that the government has\npaid out billions of dollars In re*\ncovery and relief expenditures to\nmillions of people who are custom\ners of our business men and that\nall of these billions have thus\npromptly made their way into bus\niness. We have seen also that the\ngovernment has obtained all of\nthese billions by borrowing them at\nthe banks.\nNow we can see what the effects\nof this have been.\nFirst, It Is perfectly obvious that\nthis has produced a powerful lift\nIn business. Men have gone back to\nwork and they In turn, drawing\nwages, spend those wages with the\nmerchants. And the profits of bus\niness have returned.\nSecond, certain psychological re\nsults have taken place. One is that\nthe great majority of people accept\nthis all at Its face value and say\nflatly that we have recovered. This\ncreates confidence In their minds\nand puts them in a spending mood.\nNext, a large number of more\nobserving people have concluded\nthat this immense Infusion of gov\nernment credit Is the prelude to a\nconsiderable Inflation. They believe\nthat the forces making for Inflation\nonce set In motion are too power\nful to be easily or quickly checked.\nIf inflation comes they believe,\nrightly, that prices will go up, wages\nwill go up and that, therefore, the\nvalue of the dollar will be reduced,\nThis makes them hesitant about\nlending money. Instead It encour\nages them to put their money Into\nstocks\u2014equities which have a bet\nter chance to rise with the inflation.\nThis has created a very large de\nmand for so-called good stocks.\n\u201cBiggest\u201d Boom\nWas Predicted\nThe president\u2019s money policies\nhave produced the same effect. The\npresident has devalued the dollar,\ncutting down Us gold content by 40\nper cent. Many economists and\nmany ihvestors believe this Is an in\nevitable force pressing toward Infla\ntion. It has resulted in the influx of\nFIVE BILLION DOLLARS in gold,\nanother energy working for infla\ntion.\nThen there was, beginning In\nSeptember, 1936, a very influential\nschool of financiers and economists\nwho decided that the spending\nprogram, plus the government\u2019s\nresolution to avoid taxing sis much\nas possible, plus the government\u2019s\nborrowing policies which required\nan easy money market would have\nthree effects:\n1. That we could be assured\nof easy money for some years.\n2. That the government spend\ning had primed the pump of bus\niness and that we were about to\nsee a tremendous expansion of\nthe heavy construction industries.\n3. That great shortages have\npiled up in houses, commercial\nbuilding, plant machinery, rail\nroad equipment, utility facilities\nand that these would surely re\nsult in taking advantage of the\neasy money market and the ris\ning tide of business to make large\nsecurity offerings and embark on\nextensive building programs.\nAltogether, they concluded we\nwere on the eve of the greatest\nboom in history. And they sold this\nidea to a very large number of in\nBuyers Boost Market\nHigher To Open Week\nBonds Steadier\u2014Cotton Futures Made Advance;\nRailway Shares Were Very Promnient in Upturn\nELMER C. WALKER\n(United Press Financial Editor)\nNew York, Sept. 27\u2014(UF)-Buy\ners came Into the stock market to\nday after last week\u2019s sharp declines\nand prices firmed fractions to more\nthan a point. Bonds were steadier\nwhile cotton futures advanced 50 to\n75 cents a bale.\nRailroads stocks were prominent\non the upside. Oils, utilities, steels\nand communications were firm.\nWestinghouse Electric, hard hit\nlast week, jumped 3 3-4 points to\n11374. U. S. Steel on a block of\n2,500 shares opened at 82 1-2 i:d\n2 1-2. The stock exchange Is Invest\nigating all trancatlons in steel from\nSeptember 7 to 25th inclusive to ob\ntain Information on the market\u2019s re\ncent behaviour. Bethlehem Steel\nrose 3 1-4 to 70 1-2.\nIssues to gain a point or more\nIncluded New York Central, Mont\nN. Y. Bank Trait Stocks\nThe R. F. Orlop Co.\nB