5614\nEagle Lock Co. xd. 2114 2314\nEastern Malleable Iron. 14 17\nLanders, P r a r y Sc\nClark 3014 3214\nNew Brit. Mach. Co.\ncom. 32 34\nNorth Sc Judd Mfg.\nCo. 3114 3314\nPeck, Stow Sc Wilcox\nCo. 914 1.114\nRemington Arms 3 4\nScovlll Mfg. Co. 32 34\nStanley Works Co. com. 51 53\nTorrington Co. 3014 3214\nINSURANCE STOCKS\nBid Asked\nAetna Plre Ins. 53 55\nAetna Life Ins. 2414 2614\nAutomobile Ins. 2714 2914\nConn. General 2914 3114\nHartford Fire Ins. 6414 6614\nHome Ins. 29 31\nNational Fire Ini. 5814 6014\nPhoenix Fire Ins. 78 81\nrraveleri Ins. 410 420\nTHE STOCK EXCHANGE REFLECTS FLUCTUATING ATTITUDES\nOF THE COUNTRY ABOUT THE BUSINESS OUTLOOK IN TERMS\nOF SECURITIES PRICES.\n/'GOVERNMENT spending lifted business out of the depression.\nWhy should not continued spending bring about continued im\nprovement of the industrial outlook? This is the question examined\nby John T. Flynn, famed writer on\u2018economic topics for NEA Service\nand The Waterbury Democrat, in this concluding article of his\nseries on MORE ABOUT TAXES.\nvestors up to the beginning of the\nsummer.\nAs a result of all this, In spite\nof war rumors in Asia and Europe\nand despite widespread labor trou\nbles, the stock market went up. And\nat the same time the prices of com\nmodities and retail merchandise\nwent up.\nFacts of Borrowing\nBegin to Sink In\nAnd so as this year opened the\nscene seemed set to the multitude\nfor a grand sweep forward. Now\nthen, what has actually happened!\nBusiness has gone forward. The\nsteady flow of new purchasing pow\ner has continually expanded pur\nchasing power. Then for the first\ntime since the depression private\nlending began to show Its head. The\nbanks increased loans a billion. And\nprivate building, chiefly housing, ln\ncretased. It is not true to say that\nbusiness did not go forward. It\nwent forward about as any sane ob\nerver predicted last January. But\nthe big point is that it did not go\nforward with the great bounce\nwhich the overwrought optimists\nsupposed. And as the summer\nmonths opened this fact began to\ndawn on a lot of minds.\n(1) The great boom didn\u2019t show\nup. And building, which Improved,\nceased its Improvement at the very\n1:15 P. M. PRICES\nWHITEHOUSB CO,\nAllied Chem.\nAm. Can\nAm. sm. Ref.\nAm. Tel. Tel...\nAnaconda Cop.\nAtcli. Top. S. P.\nBalt. Ohio\nBeth, steel\nBorden\nCan. Pacific\nCase Mach.\nChcs. Ohio\nChrysler Motor\nConsolldatdc Oil\nCon. Edison\nContinental Can...\nCorn Products\nDuPont..|\nEastman Kodak\nElec. Auto-Lite\nFreeport Texas\nGeneral Elec.\nGeneral Poods\nGeneral Motors\nGoodyear\nInt\u2019l Tel. Tel.\nJohns Manvllle\nKennecot Cop.\nKresge Stores\nKroger Groceries\nLamber Chem.\nLoews\nMcKesson Sc Robbins.\nMack Truck\nMont. Ward\nMurray Corp.\nNash <fc Kelvlnator\nNat'l Biscuit.\nNat\u2019l Dairy\nNat'l Pow. Sc L.\nN. Y. Central\nNew Haven R. R.\nNorth Am.\nPackard Motors\nPenn. R. R.\nPub. Ser. of N. J.\nPullman Co.\nHadlo\nSep, Iron <5: Steel\n3ears-Roebuck\nSouth Pac...\nStandard Brands\n3. O. of N. J.\n3ocony-Vacuum\n3tewart-Wamer\n3tudebaker\nrexas Corp.\nrexas Gulf\nUnion Carbide\nUnion Pacific\nUnited Air\nUnited Corp..\nUnited Gas Improved...\nU. S. Indus. Alcohol.\nU. s. Rubber\nU. S. Steel\nVanadium\nVarner Bros..\nWestern Union\niVestinghouse Elec.\nWoolworth\n-1\n184H\n92\n68 Vs\n158\n37 Si\n55%\n15%\n66 Vs\n20 Ti\nS%\n129\n39%\n88\n36 Vi\n30\n52\n56\n136\n171%\n28%\n24%\n41 Va\n33%\n47 V.\n36%\n7 Vi\n98\n44%\n20\n18\n15%\n65%\n9 Vi\n29 Vi\n44\n8\n14%\n22\n18%\n8\n26\n3%\n20\n6%\n28%\n37%\n35\n8%\n22%\n71\n29\n10%\n52%\n17%\n12%\n8%\n44%\n32%\n83%\n102%\n19%\n3%\n11%\n23\n36\n78%\n20%\n9%\n30\n110\n40%\nNEW YORK CURB\nUltles Service 3%\nElec. Bond Sc Share 11%\nNiagara Hudson Power. 10%\nmoment when it should have surged\non.\n(2) As a result of discussions the\ncountry suddenly became conscious\nof the means by whic hit had re\ncovered. In other words, the gov\nernment borrowing program came\nto be more generally understood.\nThe warnings of economists and\nothers for several years began to\nsink In.\n(3) It has also suddenly been\ndriven into the minds of business\nmen that this vast flood of credit,\nwhich drove business forward, is\nnow a burden. It was credit. It\nis now debt. It must be stopped,\nthey say. But if we stop it, what\nthen? What will take its place? If\nwe stoy using I. O. U.\u2019s we must,\nuse cash. That means taxes.\nOf course they would like to see\nspending stopped. But it can\u2019t be\nJust stopped overnight. We have\ncreated a machine which must be\nkept running and if dismantled at\nall, must be dismantled slowly.\nMoreover we have driven the whole\neconomic life of the country to a\nmuch higher price level. We have\nto keep it there. And behind all\nthis looms the ominous word\u2014TAX\nES.\n\nQuestion of Texas\nDemands Action\nThus the mind of the country\nstood and thus the price structure\nof goods and stocks stood. Had\nthere been no European or Asiatic\nscare this must have brought about\na stock market decline soon any\nway. Stocks went down because\nthey went up too fast and they went\nup on a series of false assumptions.\nThey will probably go up again a\nlittle more slowly and then topple\nagain. But in the meantime ,1s it\nnot quite plain that the nation\nmust now settle down a little sober\nly and meet these grave questions\nof taxes and national credit before\nthey go so far that dealing with\nthem will be impossible?\nSCOVILL\nMANUFACTURING\nCOMPANY\nMMOMcnnB ooooa\nHIM TO OHO\ni\nCMMl\n1 I\nThe mark that idrnitiJUi fit\nCOPPER BRASS BRONZE\nSheets Wire Rods Tubes\nFrench Small Tube Branch\nSmall Diametar.Scamleis Tubes\nWatcrbury Brass Ooods Branch\nManufactured Brass Goods\nAmerican Metal Hose Branch\nFlexible Metallic Hose\nTHE AMERICAN BRASS\nCOMPANY","height":"28004","width":"20708"}}
